Good, that's a real target. Here's a full MVP map for people stuck in tutorial hell trying to prove (to themselves and others) they can actually build things.
Core value proposition (keep this pinned above every decision)
"Take a practical, auto-graded challenge in a real skill area, and walk away with proof — for yourself and for employers — that you can actually build, not just follow along."

MVP Feature Set
1. Practical Skill Tracks (2–3 to start)
Pick narrow, high-demand tracks where tutorial-hell is most common — e.g. "REST APIs," "Frontend/JS fundamentals," "SQL & databases." Not "Web Development" as one blob — specific enough that a result means something.
2. Auto-graded Practical Assessments
The core mechanic. Not multiple choice trivia — tasks like "here's a broken endpoint, fix it," "write a query that returns X," "implement this function to pass these tests." Graded by running code against test cases / expected output, not manual review.
3. Skill Profile / Results Report
Instead of one score: a breakdown per sub-skill ("Solid: routing, validation. Weak: auth, error handling"). This is the artifact users actually want — something concrete to point to, and something that tells them what to fix next.
4. Practice Mode vs. Verified Attempt
Unlimited untimed practice per track (low-pressure, matches your "not too competitive" instinct), plus one official timed/verified attempt that generates the shareable result. Keeps pressure optional, not default.
5. Basic Account + History
Signup, track progress over time, revisit past results.
Explicitly out of scope for MVP (as discussed): custom test creation, importing external tests, sharing/social features, timed steeplechase mode. Revisit after the core loop is validated.

Functional Requirements
Auth & Accounts

FR1: User can sign up / log in (email+password, or OAuth — pick one, don't build both for MVP).
FR2: User can view/edit basic profile info.

Assessments

FR3: User can browse available skill tracks and see a description of what each covers.
FR4: User can start a practice attempt (untimed, unlimited retries) for any track.
FR5: User can start one official verified attempt per track (timed, single-take, generates a result).
FR6: System presents practical tasks (code-completion, bug-fix, query-writing, etc.) with a defined correct-output spec.
FR7: System auto-grades submissions by executing code/queries against hidden test cases and comparing output.
FR8: User receives pass/fail + partial-credit detail per task immediately after submission (practice mode) or after the attempt completes (verified mode).

Results

FR9: System generates a skill-breakdown report per completed verified attempt (sub-skill level, not just overall score).
FR10: User can view history of past attempts and track improvement over time.
FR11: User can download or view a shareable summary of a verified result (link or exportable snapshot — full sharing features like public profiles are v2, but the artifact itself should exist since "proof to show employers" is the whole point).

Admin/Content (internal, not user-facing yet)

FR12: Admin/internal team can add/edit tasks and test cases per track (since user-generated content is deferred, someone has to author the initial task bank).


Non-Functional Requirements
Security

NFR1: Code execution must run in a sandboxed, isolated environment (containerized, resource/time-limited) — this is non-negotiable since you're literally running arbitrary user code.
NFR2: Passwords hashed (bcrypt/argon2), standard auth security practices (rate limiting on login, etc.).

Performance

NFR3: Code grading feedback should return within a few seconds for a typical task (users in "practice mode" will abandon if grading feels slow).
NFR4: Platform should handle concurrent grading requests without one user's execution blocking another's (queue-based execution if needed).

Reliability

NFR5: Grading must be deterministic — same submission should always produce same result (flaky test cases will destroy trust immediately, given your whole premise is "verification").

Usability

NFR6: Task instructions must be unambiguous with visible example input/output — since these are auto-graded, unclear specs are worse here than in a human-reviewed test.
NFR7: Low-pressure framing in UI copy/design for practice mode (progress-oriented, not scoreboard-oriented) to match your explicit "not too competitive" goal.

Scalability (light touch for MVP, don't over-build)

NFR8: Architecture should allow adding new tracks/tasks without code changes (data-driven task definitions), since you'll want to expand tracks post-MVP without a rebuild.

Compliance/Data

NFR9: Basic data privacy handling (clear data retention/deletion, no unnecessary PII collection) — even pre-institutional-sale, this saves pain later.

